Marrakech,YRzBoL2qhp8,Ugxg2QZui9mnpC3C4HZ4AaABAg.AEgR4AX-KvaAEiN-ly_nD6,Ugxg2QZui9mnpC3C4HZ4AaABAg,@ReigneOrShine,Thanks for watching! 🙏🏽🙂,2025-02-19T08:33:28Z,2025-02-19T08:33:28Z,0,True,,2026-04-27T02:01:47.268435
Marrakech,YRzBoL2qhp8,UgxULS-KZjvFPBtkekJ4AaABAg.AESiE8LZBcZAESkln_kjF5,UgxULS-KZjvFPBtkekJ4AaABAg,@ReigneOrShine,"Thanks for watching. I think we have showed in the video that most local people were very friendly to us. Of course, like in all the big cities in the world, you need to have common sense. We have explained in the video about how to behave in the souks to avoid issues. Take the usual safety measures like the ones you would take visiting big cities like Rome, Paris or Madrid, just to mention some big cities we have visited in recent years, where you have to keep your belongings safe in crowded places. Do not believe scammers approaching you in the middle of the street. Do not stay alone late at night in areas where there are not many people. In our whole trip in Morocco we felt safe, you can watch the rest of our travel series to have a broader idea. We caught public buses (even at night), the train, we stayed after sunset and woke up for sunrise. Not a single issue. We met some wonderful people who just wanted to chat on the streets too. If someone suddenly offers you to bring you somewhere or to sell you something, in any country in the world, just don't trust them. If they are just curious and friendly, be open to a nice conversation. 🙂",2025-02-12T21:42:47Z,2025-02-12T21:42:47Z,0,True,,2026-04-27T02:01:47.397453
