Tourism,cRdwAQD1OKE,UgwbNcf3DHHd7kesKUt4AaABAg.AVyJt7FvF2CAVyY91jL0vE,UgwbNcf3DHHd7kesKUt4AaABAg,@NovoAurora,Where is most of the electricity coming from?😁😊,2026-04-24T04:12:24Z,2026-04-24T04:12:24Z,0,True,,2026-04-27T02:02:28.680049
Tourism,cRdwAQD1OKE,UgwbNcf3DHHd7kesKUt4AaABAg.AVyJt7FvF2CAVz6LOSnExi,UgwbNcf3DHHd7kesKUt4AaABAg,@100DOLLARCAMERA,"You are correct:  Boracay Island is primarily powered via submarine and underground cabling connected to the Panay mainland grid, rather than having its own central power station. Electricity is supplied by the Aklan Electric Cooperative (AKELCO) and the National Grid Corporation of the Philippines (NGCP), traveling from the Nabas Substation on the mainland to Caticlan, where it crosses the channel through high-voltage submarine cables. To maintain the island's aesthetic and protect the lines from the elements, much of the distribution on the island itself is handled through underground cables. As of 2026, reliability has been significantly improved by the completion of the 138-kV Nabas-Caticlan-Boracay Transmission Line Project, which reinforced the connection to the mainland to prevent the frequent blackouts of the past. While the grid utilizes a mix of energy sources from the mainland, many resorts still maintain independent diesel generators as emergency backups.",2026-04-24T09:28:40Z,2026-04-24T09:28:40Z,0,True,,2026-04-27T02:02:28.680063
