مراكش,icP4UzMdkGM,UgzwyeklM8IcINlNihN4AaABAg,,@DenizMiraaruna13,"This video is not just biased—it is intellectually dishonest. You repeatedly blur the line between Jews (an ethnic and/or religious group) and Zionists (a political ideology). That’s not a small mistake, it’s a reckless conflation that spreads ignorance and fuels hostility.

Then you go even further and frame people praying for 10–15 minutes in front of a wall as some kind of “provocation” toward Muslims. That’s not just wrong—it’s absurd. Freedom of religion doesn’t disappear because it makes you uncomfortable. They have the same right to pray as Muslims do, and pretending otherwise exposes a deeply intolerant mindset.

Your entire argument reeks of hypocrisy. You talk as if Muslims somehow “own” Morocco. They don’t. Morocco existed long before Islam, and Amazigh populations practiced diverse beliefs—paganism, Judaism, Christianity—long before Islam arrived. And yes, Islam’s expansion in North Africa wasn’t purely peaceful. Ignoring that doesn’t make it false; it just shows you’re selectively rewriting history to fit your narrative.

So let’s be consistent: if you think people shouldn’t be allowed to practice their beliefs publicly because Morocco is a “Muslim country,” then you have zero credibility demanding rights, tolerance, or freedom of expression in Western countries. You don’t get to defend oppression at home and complain about discrimination abroad.

And spare us the myth of Morocco as a beacon of tolerance. That image falls apart the moment you look at how non-Muslim Moroccans are actually treated. Many face harassment, restrictions, and constant pressure. Some can’t even practice freely—even in spaces that should be safe for worship. Moroccan Christians face real limitations on gathering, marriage, and recognition. Non-religious Moroccans are treated like second-class citizens. When they speak up, they’re told to leave their own country. That’s not tolerance—that’s exclusion.

Even Jewish communities, who were historically more protected than others, are now facing a noticeable rise in antisemitism. That alone should tell you where this mentality is heading.

And finally, stop calling Moroccans “Arabs” like it’s a fact. It’s not—it’s an oversimplification at best and erasure at worst. Morocco is fundamentally Amazigh, North African. Arab influence exists, yes, but it doesn’t erase indigenous identity. The country was heavily Arabized over time—linguistically—but that doesn’t magically rewrite origins.

And before you try the lazy comeback about language: yes, I’m using English. That’s a tool for communication, not a declaration of identity",2026-04-25T17:38:04Z,2026-04-25T17:38:04Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-27T02:05:23.273068
